Sequence analysis of the N gene PCR product showed high sequence identities (97.8% amino acid identity) with porcine coronaviruses for six cDNA samples. Phylogenetic analysis placed these sequences into one cluster and on a branch with porcine coronaviruses (Fig. 1
). One sample (04-0377) showed a 97.8% amino acid sequence identity with CCoV strains 23/03 and BGF-10. Sequence analysis and phylogenetic analysis of the M gene PCR product confirmed the close relationship of the cDNA from sample 04-0377 with CCoV strain 23/03 (90.1% amino acid identity). The M gene sequences obtained from the other five positive samples were most closely related to CCoV strain CB05 (98.1% amino acid identity) (Fig. 2
).
